  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Limited access to and sustained uptake of HIV testing, care and treatment services is perhaps the greatest barrier ARP countries face in achieving their ambitious &#x201C;Three Zeros&#x201D; targets (zero new infections, deaths, and stigma and discrimination).  Across Asia, only about 40% of individuals in need are receiving treatment, and coverage is lower among key populations facing elevated HIV acquisition and transmission risks, such as MSM, TG, SW and PWID.            

The new mechanism will focus on the development, implementation, evaluation and packaging of models for the delivery of comprehensive prevention services for key affected populations (KAPs) &#x2013; including sex workers (SW), people who inject drugs (PWID), transgender women (TG) and men who have sex with men (MSM).  These activities will focus on building capacity of civil society, actively including KAPs and people living with HIV and AIDS in policy and advocacy efforts, and engagement with host country governments in decision-making processes.  The strategy will allow for the creation and use of data-driven decision-making models with respect to KAPs, for use by both national governments and civil society. 

All activities related to model development will involve engagement with host country governments for scale-up of the models through in-country resources, including Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM) funding.  OPH&#x2019;s activities have been informed by the President&#x2019;s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) process of working with counterpart USG agencies, particularly in China, Laos, and Thailand.</narrative>
  </description>
